                <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-600 mb-10 italic border-l-4 border-medicalTeal pl-6">
                    PRP treatment is a non-surgical regenerative medical procedure that uses a concentrated preparation of your own blood platelets to accelerate healing, stimulate tissue repair, and promote natural growth in hair follicles and skin cells. Widely used across dermatology, orthopaedics, and aesthetic medicine, PRP has become one of the most sought-after treatments for <a href="../hair-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">hair loss</a> and <a href="../face-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">facial rejuvenation</a> in India.
                </p>

                <p>If you have been searching for "what is PRP treatment" and want a clear, medically accurate explanation, this guide covers everything you need to know. From the science behind platelet-rich plasma to the step-by-step process, applications, eligibility, costs, and expected results, we break it all down in simple language so you can make an informed decision about your health and appearance.</p>

                <!-- ========== PRP MEANING & FULL FORM ========== -->
                <h2>PRP Treatment Meaning and Full Form</h2>
                <p>PRP stands for <strong>Platelet-Rich Plasma</strong>. It is a component of your blood that contains a high concentration of platelets, typically 3 to 5 times more than what circulates normally. Platelets are tiny blood cells best known for clotting, but they also carry hundreds of bioactive proteins called <strong>growth factors</strong>. These growth factors, including Platelet-Derived Growth Factor (PDGF), Transforming Growth Factor-beta (TGF-b), Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor (VEGF), and Epidermal Growth Factor (EGF), play a critical role in wound healing, collagen synthesis, and cellular regeneration.</p>

                <p>When this concentrated plasma is injected into a targeted area, it triggers a cascade of biological processes that repair damaged tissue, stimulate dormant hair follicles, and rejuvenate ageing skin. To learn more about the basics, you can also read our detailed guide on <a href="what-is-prp.php">what is PRP</a> and <a href="what-is-prp-injection.php">what is PRP injection</a>.</p>

                <!-- ========== HOW PRP WORKS ========== -->
                <h2>How Does PRP Treatment Work?</h2>
                <p>The science behind PRP treatment is rooted in your body's natural healing mechanism. Here is what happens at a cellular level when PRP is administered:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Platelet Concentration:</strong> A small volume of blood is drawn and processed in a centrifuge to separate plasma layers. The platelet-rich layer is isolated, yielding a concentration that is 3 to 5 times higher than baseline levels in whole blood.</li>
                    <li><strong>Growth Factor Release:</strong> Once injected, the concentrated platelets undergo degranulation, releasing alpha granules packed with growth factors. These proteins bind to receptors on stem cells, osteoblasts, fibroblasts, and endothelial cells in the target tissue.</li>
                    <li><strong>Tissue Regeneration:</strong> Growth factors stimulate new blood vessel formation (angiogenesis), increase collagen production, accelerate cell division, and reduce inflammation. In the scalp, this revives miniaturized hair follicles and extends the growth phase (anagen) of the hair cycle.</li>
                    <li><strong>Sustained Healing:</strong> Unlike synthetic treatments, PRP provides a sustained release of growth factors over several days, creating a prolonged healing environment that supports long-term tissue repair and regeneration.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Because PRP is derived entirely from your own blood (autologous), there is virtually no risk of allergic reaction, immune rejection, or disease transmission. This makes it one of the safest regenerative therapies available today.</p>

                <!-- ========== STEP-BY-STEP PROCESS ========== -->
                <h2>PRP Treatment Process: Step-by-Step</h2>
                <p>Understanding the complete PRP treatment process helps set realistic expectations and reduces anxiety before your appointment. Here is exactly what happens during a typical PRP session at <a href="../contact.php">DenceSpot Clinic in Gurgaon</a>:</p>

                <h3>Step 1: Consultation and Assessment</h3>
                <p>Every PRP journey begins with a thorough consultation. Our dermatologist examines your scalp or skin condition, reviews your medical history, checks for contraindications such as blood disorders or active infections, and determines whether PRP is the right treatment for your specific concern. If you are seeking PRP for hair loss, a trichoscopy or hair density analysis may be performed to establish a baseline for tracking progress.</p>

                <h3>Step 2: Blood Collection</h3>
                <p>A small sample of blood, typically 15 to 20 millilitres (about 3 to 4 teaspoons), is drawn from your arm using a standard venipuncture technique. This is no different from a routine blood test and takes less than two minutes. The blood is collected in specialised PRP tubes that contain an anticoagulant to prevent premature clotting.</p>

                <h3>Step 3: Centrifugation and Platelet Separation</h3>
                <p>The blood sample is placed in a medical-grade centrifuge machine that spins at a specific speed (usually 1,500 to 3,000 RPM) for 8 to 12 minutes. This spinning process separates the blood into three distinct layers: red blood cells at the bottom, a buffy coat (white blood cells and platelets) in the middle, and platelet-poor plasma at the top. The platelet-rich layer is carefully extracted, yielding approximately 3 to 6 millilitres of concentrated PRP.</p>

                <h3>Step 4: Preparation and Activation</h3>
                <p>In some advanced protocols, the PRP is activated with calcium chloride or thrombin to initiate the release of growth factors before injection. At DenceSpot Clinic, we use the latest preparation techniques to ensure optimal platelet yield and viability for every patient.</p>

                <h3>Step 5: Application and Injection</h3>
                <p>Before injection, the treatment area is cleaned and a topical anaesthetic (numbing cream) is applied for 20 to 30 minutes to minimize discomfort. The PRP is then injected using fine needles (30 or 32 gauge) into the targeted area. For scalp treatment, injections are placed at multiple points across thinning zones at a depth of about 1 to 2 millimetres. For facial treatments, PRP may be injected directly, applied after microneedling, or used as a mask. The entire injection process takes 15 to 30 minutes depending on the area being treated.</p>

                <h3>Step 6: Post-Treatment Care</h3>
                <p>After the procedure, you can return to your normal activities immediately. There is no significant downtime. However, the following aftercare guidelines help optimize results:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Avoid washing the treated area for 12 to 24 hours</li>
                    <li>Do not apply harsh chemicals, dyes, or heat styling tools for 48 hours</li>
                    <li>Avoid strenuous exercise, saunas, and swimming pools for 24 to 48 hours</li>
                    <li>Do not take blood-thinning medications (aspirin, ibuprofen) for 3 to 5 days unless prescribed by your doctor</li>
                    <li>Mild redness, swelling, or tenderness at injection sites is normal and resolves within a day or two</li>
                </ul>

